Use the **Places API (New)** surfaces — specifically the `<gmp-place-autocomplete>` web component or `AutocompleteSuggestion.fetchAutocompleteSuggestions()` for programmatic flows. The legacy `Autocomplete` widget and `AutocompleteService` are on their way out: new Google Cloud projects **can no longer enable the legacy Places API at all** as of March 2025 [Source 2].

The modern autocomplete stack has two concrete advantages beyond just being current:

1. **Session token management is automatic** with `<gmp-place-autocomplete>` — the element handles `AutocompleteSessionToken`s internally, which bundles keystrokes + the subsequent Place Details call into one billed session. With the legacy widget you had to manage this manually, and getting it wrong means every keystroke is billed as a standalone request [Source 4].
2. **Cleaner event model** — instead of `autocomplete.addListener("place_changed", ...)` + `autocomplete.getPlace()`, you listen for `gmp-select` and call `placePrediction.toPlace()` on the event payload [Source 1].

Here's the minimal working pattern with the new element:

```javascript
// Load the places library
const { PlaceAutocompleteElement } = await google.maps.importLibrary("places");

// Or use the web component directly in HTML:
// <gmp-place-autocomplete></gmp-place-autocomplete>

const autocompleteEl = document.querySelector("gmp-place-autocomplete");

autocompleteEl.addEventListener("gmp-select", async (event) => {
  const placePrediction = event.placePrediction;

  // Convert prediction to a Place object and fetch the fields you need
  const place = placePrediction.toPlace();
  await place.fetchFields({
    fields: ["displayName", "formattedAddress", "location"],
  });

  console.log(place.displayName);
  console.log(place.formattedAddress);
  console.log(place.location.lat(), place.location.lng());
});
```

The full legacy → current mapping for reference [Source 1][Source 4]:

| Legacy | Current |
|---|---|
| `new google.maps.places.Autocomplete(input)` | `<gmp-place-autocomplete>` element |
| `addListener("place_changed", ...)` | `addEventListener("gmp-select", ...)` |
| `autocomplete.getPlace()` | `placePrediction.toPlace()` from the event |
| `AutocompleteService.getPlacePredictions()` | `AutocompleteSuggestion.fetchAutocompleteSuggestions()` |
| Manual `AutocompleteSessionToken` with the element | Not needed — managed automatically |

**Bottom line:** if you're starting a new project, you have no choice — the legacy API can't be enabled. If you're on an existing project, migrate now rather than waiting for a sunset date that hasn't been published yet.

**Sources:**
- [Places API (New)](https://developers.google.com/maps/documentation/places/web-service/overview)
- [Deprecations and Migration Guide](https://developers.google.com/maps/deprecations)
